heading.content: Case for action (What is the motivation?)

sentences.content: The model lost much of her fluency to moderately severe aphasia.
Her primary goal is to recover as much conversational speech as possible.
Fortunately, her loss of verbal skills did not include basic oral reading skills.
To work toward regaining her voice in complete sentences, she can leverage her oral reading skills with repeated practice as well as build her confidence in speaking.

Properly formatted content containing verbal and visual cues (i.e., written and oral, multimodal) allow her to practice expressing herself in full sentences confidently with better execution and fewer persistent errors.
However, her oral reading of sentences still presented several challenges with existing content, clinical or otherwise.
The following reflects the most useful practices to address the challenges observed and recommendations from her speech language pathologists.
Formatting content for the user
Font sizing
Sentence spacing
Indexing
Offering familiar and relevant content to the user
Custom content
Context, multimodal, visual, verbal
Prose structuring, lists, bullets, indenting
Tracking, recognizing and correcting the content spoken by the users
Current word tracking
Recite on demand
Special formats (e.g., dates, phone numbers.
Email addresses)
Corrections (after retries)
Word retrieval
Word fill-ins
Hints
With these specific requirements, a product search revealed no viable candidates.
Some apps could recognize words and sentences, many could generate speech, but none could host custom prose interleaved with images and support speech recognition and synthesis.
None could highlight the current word to be recited and none can support cueing hierarchies.
This seemed understandable given the specific need: reading as speech reinforcement.
Intuitively, people begin to learn or relearn how to speak through oral conversation.
The model user of this app benefits from self-paced written rote reinforcement.
When facilitating constructive reading practices, tracking the current word to be read is an obvious strategy.
The index finger of the reader seems convenient and familiar to start.
However, when self-tracking words, the model sometimes omits or misrecognizes words.

And while overlooking the occasional and arbitrary misreads seems reasonable, persistent misreads warrants more real-time and accurate feedback when the model cannot remember much less acknowledge misreads after the fact, possibly due to memory deficits.
Introducing a literate reading companion definitely improves tracking and accuracy.

However, the model becomes more frustrated with and starts arguing about the accuracy of the corrective feedback as she perceives a less supportive and understanding role of the companion whose primary role is supposedly more advocative.

Word tracking and recognition feedback by an app seems more amenable to the model, resulting in a less combative demeanor, especially when the former corporeal companion resumes a more supportive rather than therapeutic role.

heading.content: Features (What does it do to meet the needs?

sentences.content: The reading companion is a web application (app) expressly developed for the model user.

It presents multimodal personalized content to be read aloud, highlights the current word to be recited and corrects mispronunciations without a human companion through a web browser that supports ReactJS and Speech Recognition Web API.

To balance the therapeutic challenge with ongoing self doubt and resultant frustration, the reading companion affords the reader a (configurable) number of retries before the "stuck" word is recited and the next word is highlighted.
The app also can recite partial or complete sentences, paragraphs or page.
As model user worked with her speech language pathologists, additional features have been incorporated based on their recommendations to support word finding and sentence completion.
What are the key reading companion features: Recognition, Speech

First and foremost, the reading companion reads along with the user by listening while the user reads aloud, recognizes and advances the current word to be spoken to the next word, waits for the correct word to be spoken and eventually states the word after prescribed retry counts or listening duration is exceeded.
The companion can also synthesize the text to the user in different ways by reciting the:
current word
current word and advancing to the next word
current sentence upto the current word
entire sentence
entire section.
In any of these modes, the current word can either stay unchanged or advanced to the next unrecited word.
The motif and style that determines its look and feel of the application can be changed based on individual cascading stylesheets and internal application settings.
Supports recognition of alternate pronunciations based on regular expressions especially relevant for proper nouns.
cueing hierarchy
number of retries
silence timeout
Recogizes and properly interprets components of dates, years, numbers, phone numbers, email addresses, acronyms, symbols.
